        "adonis",
        "In classical mythology, Adonis is the beautiful youth born from the incestuous union of Myrrha and her father Cinyras, beloved by Venus and killed by a wild boar. Ancient alchemists adopted Adonis as a figure for the Philosophical Sun, distinct from the common sun in the sky, whose seasonal death and resurrection encode the dissolution and reconstitution of the solar principle in the Great Work. De Jong demonstrates that Maier treats Adonis, Dionysus, Osiris, and Sol as interchangeable names for the same alchemical reality, citing the verse 'All are equal to each other, Dionysus, Sol, and Adonis.' In Emblem XLI, Maier reads the boar's tusks as the sharp acid or dissolving liquid that wounds the Philosophical Sun, while Venus's attempt to revive Adonis and her staining of the white roses red with her blood encodes the transition from albedo to rubedo. The annual mourning and subsequent celebration described by Maier parallels the death-and-resurrection pattern that structures the entire second half of Atalanta Fugiens."
