        "In Ovid's Metamorphoses Book X, Atalanta is the swift-footed maiden whom no suitor can outrun until Hippomenes, aided by Venus's golden apples, distracts her from the race and wins her in marriage. Alchemical commentators before Maier, notably Robertus Vallensis in De Veritate Artis Chemicae and Jodocus Greverus in Secretum Nobilissimorum, had already read this myth as an allegory of the volatile-fixed dynamic central to the Great Work. De Jong demonstrates that Maier elevates Atalanta from an illustrative example to the organizing principle of his entire emblem book, making her flight the master metaphor for volatile Mercury that cannot be captured by brute force but only through the cunning application of Art. In the frontispiece, the three-voice fugal structure assigns Atalanta the fleeing voice that the pursuing Hippomenes (Sulphur) can only overtake with the aid of the golden apples (the catalytic agent). De Jong shows that this allegorical logic structures all fifty emblems, each of which dramatizes some aspect of the pursuit, capture, and union of the volatile and fixed principles."
